<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-696-301  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 696 301.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Dec 18 1990 v4 n42 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Officials seek help in tallying SCORES. (law enforcement agenciesseek programmer suspected of writing SCORES virus)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Norr, Henry.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesComputer CrimesProgrammersLaw EnforcementInvestigations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Henry NorrandM;Dallas -- Law-enforcement authorities here are marshaling evidence against aprogrammer suspected of writing the SCORES virus, and officials have appealedfor assistance in documenting the economic toll of the infection.andM;While the FBI and other federal agencies have been investigating the casesince SCORES surfaced in 1988, local police recently took over because thevirus is believed to have been written by an employee of EDS, the GeneralMotors data processing subsidiary located here.andM;Lt.andP;  Walt Manning of the Dallas Police Department said he is gatheringevidence of possible violations of the &quot;harmful access&quot; clause in Texas'computer-crime statute.andP;  Manning described himself and Dallas police Sgt.andO;Gary White as &quot;the only people in the whole state of Texas with specialtraining in high-tech crime.&quot;andM;Manning said he and White are consulting on the case with Apple, EDS, NASAand virus experts such as Disinfectant author John Norstad.andP;  The virus wasfirst diagnosed by Dave Lavery, a computer specialist at the space agency'sWashington headquarters, which was hit hard by the virus.andM;Because penalties are dependent on the extent of damage, Manning said, theauthorities need to document costs directly attributable to SCORES, includingthe cost of lost work time, eradication campaigns and software purchases.andO;Lavery, now manager of NASA's planetary rover program, is helping to gathersuch evidence.andP;  He invited anyone who can document expenses of at least$1,000 to contact him on AppleLink at UGO337; on America Online at NHMUG; onUsenet at dlavery@nasamail.arc.nasa.gov or by mail at NASA Headquarters,Washington, D.C.andP;  20546.andM;SCORES victims may also contact Manning or White at the Dallas PoliceDepartment, 1840 Chestnut St., Dallas, Texas 75226.andO;</TEXT></DOC>